title: 01 Christmas in L.A
Lyrics: Merry Christmas, everybody; I'm just sitting here in my apartment in Los Angeles, California; And I was thinkin' of y'all; So I decided to sing this little song; Here we go. Well, the snow is gently falling Santa's on his way; All the kiddies are tucked in In the Constitution State; But it's quite a different story here; As I'm sipping my eggnog; Santa, he don't dare come here; He can't find his way through the smog, that's right. Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; Ain't no presents for me today; Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; I check through my stocking and then I'll be on my way; Ho-ho-ho; Well, I woke up Christmas morning, And my jaw dropped in surprise; It was clear that Santa had been there; From the evidence before my eyes; Yeah, I'd been paid a visit; By the Santa of East L.A., mom! That son-of-a-gun, he stole my TV set, My stereo, and my last week's pay; Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; Ain't no presents for me today; Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; I ain't got the tree or the trim anyway; Hi, Mom, Steve, and Leaves, And Grandma and Grandpas, Uncle Rick, Aunt Bev and little John, I just wanna let you know I'm thinking of you on this Christmas. Well, I wish you all a merry, merry Christmas; And a year with good things to bring; As for all that I got this year Was a Christmas cockroach in my stocking! Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; Ain't no presents for me today; Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; I check through my stocking and hey, I'll be on my way; Christmas in L.A., Christmas in L.A.; Hey, ma, they don't even have any snow here; Christmas in L.A.; Christmas in L.A.; That's no tree, no snow, no Santa Claus, no presents, no… Christmas in L.A., no Christmas in L.A.! Bah-humbug! I'm going back to Connecticut, man; It's nice and cold, there's snow on the ground; What more could you ask for, man? Now that is Christmas.

title: dictadroid1_2014_6_28_19_54_42
Suggested title: Voice Memo on the evolution of Weezer - 2014-6-28
Fan Comment: Reflections on Weezer's evolution, how their instincts and relationship with fans has changed.
Lyrics:
(At times you've rebelled against your natural artistic impulse to try new things. 
So does that mean you've resigned to just doing what's expected of you? 
No, I think the key was to discover a way to live in the trenches with our fans. 
To live with our fans. Not be isolated in a bunker, a rehearsal space or a studio where all you have is your own instincts. 
Weezer has always, Weezer at its best has always been a communal undertaking from that first year and a half we spent in the clubs honing our craft, finding our direction, writing, rehearsing and performing our songs. We were there with our audience, it wasn't a large audience, just a few people at first but it grew to a few hundred and the community of other bands around us, all striving to make it. All of us hacking around our demo tapes and constantly getting feedback in a very natural and dynamic way. 
As a band becomes successful, it's easy for them to get separated from that community. So it's just them. Or even worse, just them and a handful of advisors who weren't there when the band first started and first found their sound and direction. And with the best of intentions, the band simply doesn't have the same instincts anymore because they're not in the same environment and the same community. 
In recent years, Weezer has perhaps by chance, but also perhaps by design, found themselves in the midst of their community. 
Of course, more and more, coming into contact more and more with fand online, but even more effectively, in person, perhaps starting with the Weezer cruise, it feels like we're all in this together again and I quite naturally want to make the music- write the songs that make us all happy. 
To bring us all joy and harmony. And to express our needs and values. This is not contrived and I do not feel like I'm resigned. It's just a natural product of living in the community. 
)

comment: again: Maslow"a preoccupation with one's own thoughts, feelings, and aneeds is not characteristic of self'actualizing individuals." /// the only way out of all of these stylistic puzzles is to follow your whims/taste. //// this has been on my mind lately "Von Neumann warns that “pure” mathematics ‘…becomes more and more purely aestheticizing, more and more purely l’art pour l’art. This need not be bad, if the field is surrounded by correlated subjects, which still have closer empirical connections, or if the discipline is under the influence of men with an exceptionally well-developed taste. But there is a grave danger that the subject will develop along the line of least resistance, that the stream, so far from its source, will separate into a multitude of insignificant branches, and that the discipline will become a great disorganized mass of details and complexities. In other words, at a great distance from its empirical source, or after much “abstract” inbreeding, a mathematical subject is in danger of degeneration. At the inception the style is usually classical; when it shows signs of becoming baroque, then the danger signal is up. It would be easy to give examples, to trace specific evolutions into the baroque and the very high baroque…’” (Poundstone, 29)
